# 4D Engine Architecture Rules

## Core Principles

### SOLID Principles
- **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)**: Each class/function should have only one reason to change
- **Open/Closed Principle (OCP)**: Open for extension, closed for modification
- **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)**: Derived classes must be substitutable for their base classes
- **Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)**: No client should depend on methods it doesn't use
- **Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)**: Depend on abstractions, not concretions

### Additional Principles
- **DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself)**: Eliminate code duplication
- **GRASP (General Responsibility Assignment Software Patterns)**: Assign responsibilities to classes/objects
- **KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid)**: Prefer simple solutions over complex ones
- **YAGNI (You Aren't Gonna Need It)**: Don't implement functionality until it's needed

## Project Structure Requirements

### Mandatory Directories
```
project/
├── src/                    # Source code
├── include/                # Header files
├── tests/                  # Unit and integration tests
├── docs/                   # Technical documentation
├── examples/               # Usage examples
├── build/                  # Build artifacts (gitignored)
├── scripts/                # Build and utility scripts
└── config/                 # Configuration files
```

### Documentation Requirements
- **README.md**: Project overview, setup, and usage
- **API_Reference.md**: Complete API documentation
- **Examples.md**: Code examples and tutorials
- **CONTRIBUTING.md**: Contribution guidelines
- **CHANGELOG.md**: Version history
- **ARCHITECTURE.md**: System design and architecture decisions

## Code Quality Standards

### File Organization
- One class per file (except for small related classes)
- Header files in `include/` with matching source in `src/`
- Test files mirror source structure in `tests/`
- Use consistent naming conventions (PascalCase for classes, camelCase for functions)

### Function Design
- Functions should be small (< 50 lines)
- Maximum 3 parameters per function
- Use meaningful names that describe intent
- Return early to reduce nesting
- Avoid side effects in pure functions

### Class Design
- Maximum 200 lines per class
- Use composition over inheritance
- Implement proper encapsulation
- Provide clear public interfaces
- Use const correctness

### Error Handling
- Use exceptions for exceptional cases only
- Provide meaningful error messages
- Log errors appropriately
- Handle errors at the appropriate level
- Never ignore errors silently

## Testing Requirements

### Test Coverage
- Minimum 80% code coverage
- Unit tests for all public methods
- Integration tests for critical paths
- Performance tests for bottlenecks
- Property-based tests where applicable

### Test Structure
- Follow AAA pattern (Arrange, Act, Assert)
- One test per behavior
- Use descriptive test names
- Keep tests independent and isolated
- Mock external dependencies

### Test Organization
```
tests/
├── unit/                   # Unit tests
├── integration/            # Integration tests
├── performance/            # Performance tests
├── fixtures/               # Test data and fixtures
└── mocks/                  # Mock objects
```

## Build and CI/CD

### Build System
- Use CMake for C++ projects
- Support multiple build configurations (Debug, Release, Profile)
- Cross-platform compatibility
- Automated dependency management
- Clear build instructions

### Continuous Integration
- Automated testing on every commit
- Code quality checks (linting, formatting)
- Security vulnerability scanning
- Performance regression testing
- Automated documentation generation

## Documentation Standards

### Code Documentation
- Document all public APIs
- Use Doxygen-style comments
- Include usage examples in comments
- Document design decisions and rationale
- Keep documentation up-to-date

### Technical Documentation
- System architecture diagrams
- Data flow diagrams
- API specifications
- Deployment guides
- Troubleshooting guides

## Performance and Optimization

### Performance Guidelines
- Profile before optimizing
- Use appropriate data structures
- Minimize memory allocations
- Cache frequently accessed data
- Use const references for large objects

### Memory Management
- Use RAII principles
- Avoid raw pointers when possible
- Use smart pointers for ownership
- Implement proper copy/move semantics
- Avoid memory leaks

## Security Considerations

### Security Best Practices
- Validate all inputs
- Use secure coding practices
- Avoid buffer overflows
- Sanitize user data
- Implement proper authentication/authorization

## Version Control

### Git Workflow
- Use feature branches
- Write descriptive commit messages
- Use conventional commits format
- Keep commits atomic
- Regular rebasing and squashing

### Code Review
- All code must be reviewed
- Use pull requests for changes
- Require approval from maintainers
- Automated checks must pass
- Document review decisions

## Monitoring and Logging

### Logging Standards
- Use appropriate log levels
- Include contextual information
- Avoid logging sensitive data
- Use structured logging
- Implement log rotation

### Monitoring
- Track key performance metrics
- Monitor error rates
- Set up alerts for critical issues
- Use health checks
- Implement graceful degradation

## Deployment and Operations

### Deployment
- Use containerization (Docker)
- Support multiple environments
- Implement blue-green deployments
- Use infrastructure as code
- Automate rollback procedures

### Configuration Management
- Use environment-specific configs
- Avoid hardcoded values
- Use configuration validation
- Support hot-reloading where appropriate
- Document all configuration options

## Code Review Checklist

Before merging any code, ensure:
- [ ] Follows SOLID principles
- [ ] No code duplication (DRY)
- [ ] Simple and clear implementation (KISS)
- [ ] Only necessary features implemented (YAGNI)
- [ ] Proper error handling
- [ ] Adequate test coverage
- [ ] Documentation updated
- [ ] Performance considerations addressed
- [ ] Security implications reviewed
- [ ] Code style consistency maintained

## Enforcement

These rules are enforced through:
- Automated linting and formatting tools
- Pre-commit hooks
- CI/CD pipeline checks
- Code review process
- Regular architecture reviews
- Documentation audits

## Exceptions

Exceptions to these rules must be:
- Documented with clear rationale
- Approved by architecture team
- Reviewed regularly
- Minimized in scope and duration
